<br>
<br>
The warm light spilled out of the thick leaded windows, stenciling a warped orange pattern on the cobbled streets of Neriak.  From his vantage point across the alley, he was able to observe his quarry undetected; the brightly lit interior intensified the already gloomy shadows, making it almost impossible to see the darkly clad stranger casing the mansion. <br>
<br>
He had spent several weeks tailing his target, learning his behavior and cataloging his habits, exposing his fatal weaknesses.  He was patient; he had all the time in the world.  He found this fop’s arrogant self-assurance amusing, though nothing so much as a grin ever crossed his face.  To him, this was a grim business.  There was no place for levity in his profession.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> His father had told him his name once, as a child, as soon as he was able to understand its power.  His father inked the name on a piece of leathery parchment, showed it to the boy and had him commit it to memory.<br>
<br>
“Your name,” he explained to the wide-eyed child, “is the source of great power.  Protect it.  Never reveal it to anyone, ever, for the demons are hungry for your spirit.  If they know your name, the sap your soul.  Learn it now, and never again speak it to anyone.”<br>
<br>
Obedient as always, the boy stared at the henna etchings on the hide, letting the letters burn themselves into his memory before – at his father’s urging – swallowed the scrap to hide his name inside himself forever.  </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
He knew the target’s name: Kandalor D’rova, a dealer in arcane antiquities who serviced the social elite of Neriak.  In addition to the usual trade in totems, amulets, and curios D’rova also peddled older, darker artifacts that were obtained illegally.  His customers paid a premium for these rare items, as their sinister origins added great prestige – a vital commodity in a vain society built on competing houses jockeying for social position.<br>
<br>
D’rova maintained a small army of personal guards, henchmen, and advisors – more as a symbol of his wealth than out of any real necessity.  His success in the black market and his creature comforts had made him greedy for more, as the former shopkeeper had clawed his way to the inner circle of Neriak’s elite.  His humble past was a closely guarded secret, a stigma that was a sure path to social ruin, and D’rova was ruthless in acquiring more wealth in an attempt to shore up his claim to fame.<br>
<br>
His avarice had led him to make one mistake, however; a mistake that tonight would ultimately prove fatal.  D’rova had broken the taboo.  He had stolen from the stranger’s people.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Since he was old enough to stand, the boy had been trained.  His family had long served the city, and the tradition would continue with him.  His days were long and arduous, from sun up to sunset, as he was molded to fit the position he would assume when he reached manhood.<br>
<br>
From his father, he learned the paths and ways of the Otherworld, from the passage of the soul beyond to the proper charms and wardings to protect oneself from the wrath of ghosts and demons.  He learned how to prepare and dress the corpse for its final journey, and he grew familiar with the many rites and rituals that his people used.<br>
<br>
He was trained in the ways of death as well, learning countless ways to end a life and a thousand methods of bringing the subject back from the brink long enough to interrogate.  He was trained in knife, sword, and staff, practicing in the sun-baked sand until he grew numb from the effort.<br>
<br>
At night, he’d retire to his small room, poring over the ancient texts his father would assign to him, learning philosophy, science, and arcane mysteries until the candle guttered and he dropped into a deep sleep at his desk.<br>
<br>
One day, he approached his Master on the training ground, clad only in a loincloth and his sparring gloves.  Instead of the dueling knives however, his trainer held only a robe and a circlet of vicious thorny branches.  His preparation was done.  It was time for him to pass on. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The stranger watched D’rova through the panes of glass.  The feast had gone on for hours, and appeared now to be winding down.  D’rova was draping a fat, flabby arm around the shoulder of one of his shapely female guests, whispering excitedly into her ear his foul intentions.  She giggled and blushed, coyly playing along, but from his remote vantage point the assassin could see the look of frightened revulsion beneath her come-hither mask; the shuddering disgust at the greasy purple lips that hovered so close to her cheek.<br>
<br>
She would sell herself to him this night, he was sure of that.  Despite her instinct to run, despite her obvious loathing of this revolting creature, she would bed him in a bid to improve her standing among the vacuous idle nobility of the city.  She would lie still and make all the right noises as he pawed grotesquely at her with his greasy fingers, his blemished face twisted into a rictus mask of fear, hatred, and lust.  She would sell herself to this beast for the price of a fantasy.<br>
<br>
The stranger sneered at the depravity of it all.  This city was soft.  The nobility so debauched and decadent that they never even realized how ludicrous they’d become.  Their false airs and pathetic social politicking did nothing more than refresh the façade of success while their grand Houses slid into a slow, irreversible rot.  <br>
<br>
D’rova dragged the lithe beauty to her feet, leading her up the curving staircase near the back of the room while the party guests gorged themselves on the rich feast in front of them.  Several of the attendees made surreptitious note of D’rova’s departure, no doubt cataloging the event in the hopes that they could play the card in the future to advance their own position.<br>
<br>
The assassin waited a moment, then slid out of the alley as silent as a ghost.  He walked down the streets until he was sure he was not being observed before doubling back down a rubbish-strewn alley.  Flitting from shadow to shadow, he worked his way to the cellar door of D’rova’s mansion.<br>
<br>
It was time to work.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The preparation chambers were cold, much colder than he remembered.  He had been in these rooms a thousand times during the lessons with his father, but they seemed strange and alien to him this time.  The shadowy corners, thrown into sharp contrast by the whale oil lanterns, seemed to house an army of malevolent spirits, peering excitedly at his vulnerable form.  The giant, looming statues of the gods glared down at him from on high; red, angry eyes staring out of the heads of jackals and hawks.<br>
<br>
He knelt inside the painted circle, a small wooden bowl placed carefully on a copper tray in front of him.  At his father’s signal, he lifted the simple vessel and quaffed the thick, foul tasting concoction within.  <br>
<br>
Almost immediately, his head began to swim.  His throat constricted and his breathing became quick and shallow.  The shadows of the room seemed to reach out towards him, inky black fingers seeking out his warmth.  He felt the strength seep from him, flowing from his fingers and toes and running like rivers of black mercury to feed the hungry shadows.  Darkness crept in from the corners of his vision.  With a final lurch, all went black.<br>
<br>
When he awoke, he had been stretched out on the ancient limestone altar in the center of the chamber.  Stripped naked, he could feel the chill stone beneath him and the distant warmth of the smoky, oily lanterns.  He felt disconnected from his own body, yet he was more aware of every inch of skin that he had ever been.  Every sensation had been heightened beyond normal endurance, but yet he remained an impartial observer.  He could not move, could not speak, could not will his body to rouse itself from the altar and head to the safety of the city.<br>
<br>
The crown of thorns stabbed cruelly into his shaved head, lancets of pain arcing through his body as every breath forced them deeper into his skin.  The chilling cold of the slab burned with an unbearable intensity, setting his hair on end and making his skin crawl unnaturally.<br>
<br>
Saryn’s Kiss, he realized, recognizing the textbook effects of the poison, an effective aid to interrogation and torture.  The mind was removed from the body, preventing the subject from passing out from the unbelievable pain to follow, for the proper application of the poison heightened the five senses beyond reason.  The Kiss’ hallucinogenic properties heightened the brain’s activity, keeping the subject’s mind flooded in a massive sensory overload while preventing him from taking the easy way out.<br>
<br>
His father entered the room, dressed in his ceremonial robes and wielding a long, curved knife.  From the shadows behind him trailed a tall, elegant woman shrouded in a smoky grey cowl.  He could not make out her face, but her dark piercing eyes burned with an intense excitement as she glided easily across the stone floor.<br>
<br>
The attendants began lighting incense in the censers, filling the room with a thick, heavy perfume.  The woman reached out slowly, dragging her cruel fingers against his flesh.  Rivers of agony followed in their wake, as the frigid cold of her hands burned against him.  His heart began to beat wildly in his chest.  She leaned in closer to him, the thick cowl hiding her features in inky black shadows.  He struggled to breathe, feeling his very life being drawn out of him and into the coal-black pits of her eyes – almond-shaped abysses that seemed to swallow any light in the room. <br>
<br>
Silently, she touched her ice-cold fingertips to his lips, leaving blisters on his face where they lay.  She retreated again into darkness as his father slowly advanced on him with the cruel glint of the sacrificial blade. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The revelry above masked his passing.  All of the guests were either half-blind with drink or else too occupied plotting against their neighbor to take notice of him passing through the servants’ corridors, swiftly and silently, and heading up the narrow service staircase.  He eased open the door to the storage room he had prepared before, slipped inside, and quietly closed and locked the door.  Moving to the back corner of the cluttered room, he climbed atop a barrel of rum to move aside a ceiling tile.  Hoisting himself into the hole in the roof, he replaced the tile, plunging the attic crawlspace into darkness.<br>
<br>
Pinpoints of light flared up with narrow javelins of light from below, tiny peepholes he had cautiously bored over the course of the past weeks.  With well-practiced steps, he picked his way across the jumbled maze of ceiling joists to the far corner of the attic.  The roof sloped to a sharp angle here, forcing him to crawl along like a spider, clinging precariously to the woodwork around him.<br>
<br>
He brought his eye to one of his peepholes, dimly lit from below by the ambient light of a streetlamp outside.  The room itself was dark, the window open to allow the stink of his lustful exertion to pollute the air of the city.<br>
<br>
Looking onto the bed below, he could see D’rova and his consort tangled in the twisted sheets, spent already.  Regret was already beginning to etch itself on the woman’s face – she realized that she had sold herself too cheaply, realized that the pig of a man would not give up power or wealth so easily.  Revulsion was clearly visible in her eyes, but she seemed determined to save face, to continue this obscene farce in order to save some shred of dignity in the eyes of the people downstairs.  D’rova seemed to take delight in her discomfort, staring at the ceiling with half-closed eyes, leisurely stroking his chest while taking long drags on his opium pipe.<br>
<br>
The assassin was pleased.  Smoking the pipe was one of D’rova’s hidden vices.  He had correctly identified it as a potential way to get to his target, and it seemed his intuition had paid off.  Two nights before, he had dared to enter the room below to lace the stem of the pipe with a powerful poison, not altogether dissimilar from Saryn’s Kiss.  In a few moments, both whore and pig would be locked in a living nightmare.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The knife entered his body, just below the sternum, sending a lightning bolt of pure, unadulterated agony through his body.  He watched as the attendants rushed forward to hold down his arms and legs, as he began to thrash with the pain.  The effects of the drug amplified every noise, every contact, and every smell… the stink of their sweat and of his fear and blood drove him into a frenzy, while their firm, calloused hands threatened to crush his bones in their vice-like grips.<br>
<br>
With the sound of tearing canvas, the blade dragged down the length of his abdomen, and he watched with horror as his own innards burst forth from the wound as if they were trying to escape.  The woman, watching the procedure with intense interest, was rubbing her hands in anticipation.<br>
<br>
He tried to scream, but he couldn’t open his mouth.  Eyes wide with fear and shock, he pressed his tongue forward, feeling the coarse hemp thread that had sewn his mouth closed.  <br>
<br>
Deep in his gut, he felt the curved shears of his father’s trade snipping away at him, casually removing his organs as if from a corpse.  Only he was not dead, and he did not die.  The pain and agony was overwhelming, yet the drug kept him alert.  Death and unconsciousness were escapes forbidden by this darkest of rituals.  He would live through this, he was sure of that, or at least what was left of him would.<br>
<br>
Panting, heaving, he watched in terror as his life essence was lifted from his body in bloody clumps.  His father placed the organs in small stone jars arrayed on the side table, white limestone urns with jade inlays.  The cold air of the chambers flooded into his open wounds, stealing his warmth and filling him with a chill dread that made his bones ache.<br>
<br>
After an eternity, his father stopped.  Dipping his hands in a shallow bowl of water, his father surveyed his handiwork while the young man lay hollowed out on the slab, panting desperately to fill lungs that no longer existed.  His head swam, the loss of blood causing him to lose focus, the terrible acuity of the procedure’s pain receding into a dull, throbbing ache that caused his ears to pound and his jaw to grind behind his bound lips.<br>
<br>
“Sew him up,” his father said, “and seal him in the sarcophagus.  He must now dream.”<br>
<br>
Hurriedly, the aides worked to stitch together his wound, the skin and muscle sagging sickeningly into the hollow void of his empty abdomen.  His father left the room, accepting the somber congratulations from the attendants.  The procedure had been a success, and now his only son was going to be an offering to their Great Mistress.<br>
<br>
They transferred him from the slab to a narrow canvas stretcher.  Moving silently and with great skill, they carried him out of the preparation chamber and into the canal room next door, where a long curved boat sat waiting in the narrow channel.  Two attendants loaded him into the boat and prepared to embark.<br>
<br>
Unable to move his head, he lay staring at the high, dark ceiling inlaid with pearls to reflect the night sky over the necropolis.  The canal was narrow and shallow, filled with the flowing seawater that encircled their ancient city.  Dark red sandstone, untouched by the blistering sun, reflected the greasy light cast down by the oil lanterns, revealing the deep black mouth of the tunnel on the far side of the room.  Through there the canal ran, where the dead would be taken to their final resting place, taken to their eternal slumber, and delivered into the waiting arms of Terris Thule.<br>
<br>
The woman in grey crossed the chamber and boarded the narrow ship, seemingly floating over the ground as her dark, ethereal dress reached the very floor.  She sat on a small stool by his head, and touched a gentle finger to his lips.<br>
<br>
“Sleep,” she said quietly, her voice a mere whisper across his fevered brain.  “Sleep, my son, and dream.” </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
D’rova and his woman were awake, he knew that.  But he also knew that the terror scenes that they were seeing were twisted caricatures of reality, tempered by their deepest and darkest fears.  Their own minds were dredging up years of fear and loathing and hate and repressed emotion and weaving them all into macabre mindplays that they were helpless to escape.<br>
<br>
He regretted having to entrap the woman in such matters as these, but it could not be helped.  He was to eliminate the target, and any who got in the way.  She was an unfortunate obstacle… she would live, but the lingering effects of the poison, combined with what she was about to see, would likely shatter her rational mind.  She came to his bed in an attempt to gain notoriety, he mused, but she would leave in infamy.<br>
<br>
He moved a ceiling tile aside and dropped to the ground silently.  Wrapped in their own nightmares, the D’rova and the woman hardly reacted, merely flinching and cowering as he was assimilated into their visions.  He quickly checked the door to make sure it was bolted from the inside before pulling a small vial of a foul green liquid from his belt.  He ripped off the cap of the vial, exposing a short hooked needle at the end.<br>
<br>
Jabbing the vicious needle violently into D’rova’s neck prompted an immediate reaction.  He gasped loudly, reaching his around his throat and arching his back as his body was wracked with agonizing pain.  The woman curled up into a tight fetal ball, attempting to hide from the horrible visions the drug had wrenched out of her dark subconscious.  But there was no such escape for D’rova, as the stranger grasped his jaw roughly and twisted his face to his own.  Eyes open wide, whites showing all around, D’rova was looking into the assassin’s expressionless face.<br>
<br>
“Kandalor D’rova,” he said quietly, lowering his face to D’rova’s, “you are going to die tonight.  You – and others in your employ – have desecrated the tombs of my people.”<br>
<br>
The Tier’Dal on the bed began to bleat in protest, but the assassin squeezed his jaw tightly.  Reaching back into his pack, he withdrew a small stone vase, artfully engraved with jade and gemstones.<br>
<br>
“You sold this, as well as other funerary goods, to individuals in Neriak, Paineel, Freeport, and Highkeep.  I’ve tracked most of them down Kandalor D’rova, and they all came from your organization.  Your greed has deprived my people of their eternal dreams.  And for that, you will die.”<br>
<br>
The girl whimpered, having slid off the bed and huddled in the corner.  D’rova simply paled.  It was inevitable.<br>
<br>
He pulled the long, curved knife from his scabbard slowly.  Ritual requires precision and attention to detail.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>He had no idea how long he was sealed in the tomb.  It could have been months, it could have been days.  It could have been an eternity.  Time had no meaning to him.  Endless moments stretched out into infinity as his life played out in front of him in an eternal puppet show of twisted scenery and misshapen freaks as the actors.  His mind opened itself, and a lifetime of forgotten horrors spilled into the empty space of the sarcophagus; frozen in time like bugs in amber.<br>
<br>
The stone lid of the sarcophagus slid aside, and the sudden light of the lanterns blinded him.  Standing at the coffin edge was his Great Mistress, Terris Thule.  Draped in a dark grey shawl, she appraised him as he lay before her, her empty eyes measuring his worth.  Her featureless face belied no emotion.<br>
<br>
She extended one hand down to him, a gentle hand to lift him out of his early tomb.  He stood in the middle of the room, empty and naked, shivering in the subterranean gloom.  She stood behind him, wrapping her arms around his waist and running her fingers along the long, angry welt of his ravaged abdomen.<br>
<br>
Laying her chin against his shoulder, she explored his sutures with searching hands, plunging her fingers into the empty cavity.<br>
<br>
“You are mine now,” she said, a soft voice inside his head, “trapped between life and death.  You will never know either again, my dear.  You are doomed forever to walk in the mists of eternal dreams, forever hungering for the warmth of the life that was sacrificed to me.  Forever longing for the sweet embrace of a final death.  <br>
<br>
You are now Sohkar.  As thousands have been before you, now you are.  You are no longer bound to the living, nor are you entombed as the dead.”<br>
<br>
She chuckled, a sound that sent a shiver up his spine.  “Go forth, Sohkar, and be my Champion.  Walk the shadows and bring dread to those that hear your name.  Forever you will seek to slake the thirst inside you; forever you will seek to fill the void inside your body.  Go forth and bring to your foes eternal nightmare.” </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The early morning patrol responded to the call.  Kandalor D’rova, a wealthy and well-known art dealer, had last been seen going to his private chambers with a young female from one of the minor houses.  D’rova had not responded to his servants the next morning, though the woman could be heard crying inside.  The door, bolted on the inside, had to be knocked down with a battering ram.<br>
<br>
The carnage inside was beyond description.  The woman, in hysterics, could only point to the tangled mess that was D’rova, ripped open from sternum to groin, with his entrails strewn about the room.  Amazingly, D’rova was still alive at the time, though any hope of recovery was out of the question.<br>
<br>
D’rova was put out of his misery by the captain of the guard.  The woman was put in the care of her parents, with the strong advice that she be surrendered into the care of the proprietress of the Maiden’s Fancy, where at least she could be put to some use.<br>
<br>
There remain no clues as to the identity of the killer, or any signs of a motive.<br>
