<br>
Sohkar sat bolt upright in bed, gasping in sudden agony as another spasm of pain clutched him roughly.  His body doubled over, sweat-sodden sheets wrapping around him, clutching his limbs as he struggled to catch his breath through grinding teeth.  He fought against the grinding, blazing sensation in his gut, grabbing at an invisible wound to hold in phantom entrails.  Sweat poured off his face as small noises escaped from his clenched jaw.  The crippling pain slicing through him like a scythe through grain; he dug his fingers into his sheets, trying to expel the pain through sheer force of will.<br>
<br>
Another wave of agony sent him sprawling to the floor, dragging his linens and his thin mattress to the bare floorboards.  The demons inside him laughed at his suffering, clawing eagerly at his stomach with jagged talons.  Whimpering, fighting the urge to scream in pain, he dragged himself to the end table, desperate hands searching frantically for the cool, cruel comfort of his pipe.  His hands danced along the tabletop, knocking over the shrouded lantern, upending a small stone charm he used to ward off evil spirits, and sending his water glass crashing to the floor.<br>
<br>
As his clambering fingers finally closed around the short, clay pipe and the weather-beaten oilskin pouch, tears sprang to his eyes.  Agonizing bands of pain wracked his body with sudden, vengeful thrusts but he managed a tortured smile as he crawled haltingly to the corner with his precious implements.  Face screwed up in absolute, defiant concentration against the shuddering pain, Sohkar carefully crammed the aromatic weed into the small hollow at the top of the pipe.<br>
<br>
Fumbling with the flints, he finally managed to light the twisted leaves; a dull red glow shining from within the body of the pipe glaring balefully back at him through the darkened room.  Part of him fought in vain against the overwhelming urge to inhale, to quell the demons within in a wave of soothing forgetfulness; part of him screaming against the roaring winds that scoured his insides like a vicious sandstorm.<br>
<br>
But he could not resist.  The was pain too great, and salvation too near.<br>
<br>
The clay touched his lips and the pain subsided; thick grey smoke rushing into his chest to fill the hungry void in the pit of his stomach.  Sohkar leaned against the cool walls, feeling the weight of the smoky waves smother the pain; the paroxysms slowed as the agony was slowly pressed into a dull throbbing ache.  He began to shiver in the unnatural subterranean cool of Neriak, the sepulcher gloom creeping into his bones.<br>
<br>
He took another deep drag off of the pipe, willing the harsh smoke to warm the emptiness inside; one more hit and he surrendered himself to the gentle relief of the Sheppen.  Heavy lidded eyes watched with detached interest as the room lost focus in subtle passes, quietly blurring into a blue-green haze until….<br>
<br>
Oblivion.<br>
