<br>
Never did he feel so alienated from the rest of his race than when he sat down to eat his morning meal. In Dayr al’Madinah, breakfast was limited to the thick, fragrant coffee, strips of dried, salted fish and perhaps a small handful of dates or dried apricots.  Here, however, the daily spread was incredibly lavish – eggs, bacon, toast, bowls of cereals and fruits, slabs of sausage meats, and anything else he could imagine.  Of course, he had to suffer through cup after cup of the tasteless dishwater they called coffee, but he considered it a small price to pay for such a bountiful feast every morning.<br>
<br>
They may hole themselves up in this dank self-imposed dungeon, and their society may be slowly rotting from the inside out with the self-indulgent games between noble houses, but the Teir’Dal of Neriak certainly knew how to start a day off right.<br>
<br>
Sohkar halfheartedly scanned the newssheet someone had left on the table, far more absorbed in the taste of his eggs than in the breathless reports of the shallow posturing of one noble house against another.  He did read, with some interest, that there had been a third murder in the city in the style he had used to dispatch D’Rova.  Sohkar didn’t know whether to be amused or horrified that some psychopathic assassin out there was glomming onto the ritual sacrifice of a tomb robber as some form of a personal calling card.<br>
<br>
Shoveling more eggs onto his fork with his third piece of buttered toast, he chuckled to himself when he thought of how the Ebon Mask would react when the copycat was finally caught.  Sohkar had taken great care to cover his tracks with the guildmasters here, knowing how sensitive they could be about foreign agents in their midst.  He was well aware that he was being followed now, which served his purposes well enough – he had an alibi that would distance himself from the unrest caused by this self-styled public menace.<br>
<br>
Tossing the dregs of his tasteless coffee into the pot of a nearby fern – much to the consternation of his landlady, who glared at him openly from behind the bar – he pushed himself away from his corner table and swept his cloak from the back of his chair.  He had a long day ahead of him, and now that his work was done it was time for him to head back to the desert and away from this dismal place.  <br>
<br>
He fastened the hooded cloak around his shoulders as he weaved through the tables that were scattered throughout the inn’s great room.  He ostensibly wore the heavy drape to protect him from the gloomy chill of the cavern-city, but he felt relief in the way the dark cowl allowed him a sense of anonymity in this nest of idle intrigue and curious plotters looking for any advantage they could use to climb their infernal social ladders.  And Sohkar – a rare visitor from the isolated Tier’Dal settlements in the Southern Desert of Ro – certainly drew more attention than he was comfortable with.  Gaunt and darkly-colored, even by Neriak standards, he stood out as an outsider even before one noticed his shaved head and the malachite he wore around his eyes.  At home, he’d be considered non-descript and hardly worth notice.  Here, he was an oddity; a curious object to be displayed at cocktail parties.<br>
<br>
He had played up his assumed role as a peddler of antiquities to get close enough to D’Rova to make good on his assignment.  He made a point of wearing the formal robes of the priests of the necropolis, as these tended to draw the attention of the vain and fashion-conscious fops he was forced to pump surreptitiously for information.  He wore the malachite, used to protect his people’s sensitive eyes from the harsh glare of the sun, even indoors.  Jewelry clattered noisily on his wrists and his outrageously thick accent sounded like a cruel parody to his ears.<br>
<br>
He felt like a right ass, and he was more than happy to be getting out of the city.  He wanted nothing more than to strip himself of these ridiculous trappings – to cease being a caricature among a throng of self-absorbed fools – and get back to Dayr al’Madinah, a small hamlet in the desert where everybody worked together for the good of the necropolis, an artisans’ village dedicated to the art and craft of the Eternal Sleep.<br>
<br>
The warmth of the great room vanished the second as he opened the door to the gloomy street, as the clinging mists of Neriak rolled over him like a great wave.  Grimacing at the sudden cold, Sohkar felt the pressing weight of the rock walls of the cavern and the creeping chill of the subterranean air.  Hissing a silent curse, he pulled the cloak tighter around him and made a beeline for the Blind Fish, where he was hoping to find notice of a caravan heading south.  To think that this unchanging gloom and damp cold permeated the city while outside it was breezy and sunny!  <br>
<br>
At least the Foreign Quarter was warm, he thought as he strode past the waterfall that filled the Commons with its blasted grey mist.  So what if it’s just the heat of forge fires and bitter resentment, he chuckled grimly, who cares if it has all the atmosphere of a troll’s armpit?<br>
<br>
There were only a scattered handful of people in the pub, but whether they were finishing off last night’s revelry or picking over the scant breakfast offerings Sohkar could not tell.  It was too early for most of the city to be up and about yet, and the few people who were awake bore every sign of wishing they weren’t.  <br>
<br>
Inwardly, he smiled.  Many of the cities famous nocturnal activities had been curtailed over the recent weeks, as authorities cracked down on the copycat killer that had been picking off wealthy merchants and traders.  HIS copycat, he noted with a flush of pride.  Though by what he could gleam from the reports, the imposter was clearly an amateur who attacked without any real planning, but he was doing a masterful job of avoiding both the city guards and the Ebon Mask.  The Mask was certainly the more dangerous of the two, he thought; there was nothing quite like a bunch of territorial professionals exacting vigilante justice.<br>
<br>
He paused in front of the message board, tapping his teeth with his thumbnail.  In retrospect, he was glad that he had gone to the Ebon Mask as soon as he had arrived in Neriak.  His absurd disguise and cover story of a traveling importer may have fooled the city’s upper crust, but he’d have been targeted very early by the suspicious and diligent agents of the Mask.  But he was here under their graces, and under their surveillance.  D’Rova was a sanctioned kill, though his … exuberance… in the method was met with some raised eyebrows at the end.<br>
<br>
Still, the copycat was creating a rock-solid alibi for him and for the Ebon Mask.  Now both parties could deny any culpability as the public outcry got louder.  In a city built on murder and treachery, it surprised Sohkar how quickly the nobles got antsy when a few of their own were being hunted by someone not playing by the inane rules of their lofty games.  But one or two high officials wake up with their entrails tacked to the ceiling, and the whole city shifts into mass paranoia.  He loved it.  He could only imagine the nightmares and shaking terrors these people had, cowering under their cover in their silken nightshirts, terrified that their creature comforts would come to naught when faced with the cold steel edge of mortality.<br>
<br>
But that was neither here nor there.  Not any more.  He was going to sign on to one of these outbound caravans and put this place behind him.  He was going to go back to the warm stone temples of the necropolis - Biban el-Muluk – and the comfortable houses of the artisans’ village.  He was finally leaving, and he was going back home.<br>
